Part I - Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Oumayma Jribi¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual trips made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

Quality issue:¶

start_time and end_time should be of type datetime and not object.

Code:¶

Created a function that takes the dataframe and a column and changes the data type of that column to datetime:

In [54]:
def dt(df,x):
    df[x]=pd.to_datetime(df[x])
In [55]:
dt(bike_data,'start_time')
dt(bike_data,'end_time')

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset contains information about 156090 bike rides with 16 features (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender).

There are 7 object type variables, and 9 numerical variables.

user_type and member_gender are categorical nominal variables, with:

  • user_type: Subscriber (member in the system) - Customer (casual user)
  • member_gender: Male - Female - Other

The variable bike_share_for_all_trips indicates whether a member is enrolled in the Bike Share for All program for low-income residents.
It takes the values of Yes-No .

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Through investigating this dataset, I'm most interested in knowing what affects the trip duration (duration_sec)

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features I'm interested in and that I think might have a relationship with the variable of interest are:

  • member gender
  • member birth year
  • starting stations
  • user types
  • enrollment in the bike share program

Univariate Exploration¶

Q: How is the distribution of the duration of bike rides (duration_sec)?¶
In [57]:
bins = np.arange(0, bike_data['duration_sec'].max()+500, 50)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = bike_data, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.title('Distribution of Trip Durations')
plt.xlabel('Trip duration (sec)')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')

#set axis limits
plt.axis([0, 4000, 0, 15000])
plt.show()

There is a long tail in the distribution (left skewed) so let's put it to log scale:

In [58]:
#create bins for the logged values
log_binsize = 0.025
bins = 10 ** np.arange(np.log10(bike_data['duration_sec'].min()),
                       np.log10(bike_data['duration_sec'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = bike_data, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')

plt.xticks([100,250, 500, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4, 2e4], [100,250, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, 10000, 20000])
plt.title('Distribution of Trip Durations')
plt.xlabel('Trip duration (sec)')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show();

When plotted on the log scale, the data points came out normally distributed. There is one peak roughly between 400 and 700 seconds, this shows that most people tend to use bikes for short durations (7 to 12 minutes).

Q: I want to check if the day hours affect the trip duration:¶

I start by creating a new column named 'start_hour' containing the starting hour of the trip:

In [81]:
import datetime
from datetime import *
In [82]:
#Creating a function that fills a second column with the hours from the first column of type datetime
def hour(nc,oc,df):
    for i in np.arange(0,len(df),1):
        nc[i]=(str(pd.to_datetime(oc[i])).split()[1].split(':')[0])
In [83]:
#creating a new column 'start_hour' and initially assigning it the values of 'start_time'
bike_data['start_hour']=bike_data['start_time']

#Filling the new column 'start_hour' with hours using the function defined above
hour(bike_data['start_hour'],bike_data['start_time'],bike_data)

g.set(xscale = 'log')
x_ticks = [500,1000,1500,2000]
plt.xticks([10**2,10**3,10**4,10**5], x_ticks)

g.fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.95) 
g.fig.suptitle('Trip duration against hours of the day')
g.add_legend();

It can be seen from the graphs that some hours have more frequent trips like: 16, 17, 18 o'clock and 7, 8, and 9 o'clock.
This can be understood as these hours correspond to the evening and morning rush hours respectively.
However, the distribution of trip durations seems to be the same for all hours of the day.

  • Although members of gender type "Other" are a minority, it was shown that they have the longet trip duration with an average of approximately 1000 seconds.
    When comparing only males and females, females seem to have a slightly higher average trip duration.
  • When studying the relationship of trip duration with birth year, there seems to be a constant range of average trip duration except for 2 peaks for the years 1988 and 2000.
  • Customers have longer trip durations than subscribers

Multivariate Exploration¶

Q: Does the member gender and birth year (age) affect trip duration?¶

In [87]:
#Creating a sample containg birth year between 1980 and 2000 and trip durations from 0 to 5000 seconds
sample=bike_data[(bike_data["member_birth_year"].isin(np.arange(1980,2001,1))) &
                 (bike_data["duration_sec"].isin(np.arange(0,5001,1)))]

#Creating the mean values that will show inside the heatmap
duration_means = sample.groupby(['member_gender', 'member_birth_year']).mean()['duration_sec']
duration_means = duration_means.reset_index(name = 'duration_avg')
duration_means = duration_means.pivot(index = 'member_gender', columns = 'member_birth_year',
                            values = 'duration_avg')

#Plotting
ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 8))
ax=sb.heatmap(duration_means,  fmt = '.3f', cmap = sb.cm.rocket_r, annot=True,
           cbar_kws = {'label' : 'mean(duration_sec)'}, annot_kws={'rotation': 90})

plt.title('Trip duration against member gender and birth year');
  • Younger females seem to have longer trip durations.
  • Males have slightly higher trip durations than the average for those born between 1988 and 1992, as well as those born on 2000.
  • For the gender type "Other", highest trip durations are for members born on 1989, 1999, followed by the years 1194, 1998, and 1993.

Conclusions¶

Steps undertaken:¶

  • I started by investigating the dataset and doing the necessary wrangling and cleaning
  • My main feature of interest was the trip duration, and through the univariate, bivariate and multivariate phases, I tried to investigate the relationship between this feature and other variables that thought might have an effect on it, mainly: member gender, member birth year, starting stations, user types, and enrollment in the bike share program.

Interesting findings:¶

  • Finding out that customers have longer trip durations can be further investigated. For example we can look for why customers have long trip durations and how to make them subscribers.
  • Members born on 1988 and 2000 have the highest trip durations
  • Some stations have higher averge trip durations than others
  • Hours of the day may have an effect on the frequency of the trips but not on the trip duration
  • Trip duration may depend on age for Females and the "Other" gender.
  • Finding out what stations are assigned with the highest trip durations for those enrolled in the bike share system might reflect where enrollers of this program are located and where they use the system most.
